By JONATHAN FOREMAN <br>
<br>
April 25, 2003 -- BAGHDAD - The Scouts of the 4th Battalion/64th Armored Regiment headed off in their Humvees yesterday on a &quot;presence patrol.&quot; Their destination: the New Market district of Baghdad, one of the poorest neighborhoods on the West Bank of the Tigris. <br>
<br>
And once again they couldn't believe the movie-star treatment they received along the way. <br>
<br>
There were cheers as they drove through the streets. Passing drivers tooted their horns or gave them the thumbs up. Children waved frantically. Old men came up to shake their hands or kiss their cheeks. <br>
<br>
Even women waved from high windows or lifted their veils to show a flirtatious smile. <br>
<br>
 <br>
<br>
And when they reached the trash-choked streets of New Market and parked their four Humvees, they were immediately mobbed. <br>
<br>
&quot;I couldn't believe it. These guys came up and kissed the flag on my shoulder!&quot; said Specialist Steve Beaman. <br>
<br>
The troops had no interpreter with them, but an English speaker was found among the locals: Hazeh Raheed, a chemist by training. Through him, a meeting was arranged with community leaders at the local barber shop. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Outside the shop, the crowd began calling out &quot;Mike Tyson!&quot; and &quot;Michael Jackson!&quot; at the only black soldier present, Staff Sgt. Darren Swain. When he told them his name, they started chanting, &quot;Swain! Swain! Swain!&quot; </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Inside the shop, Staff Sgt. Craig Hobbs - a veteran of peacekeeping in Bosnia - represented the Army. <br>
<br>
Through Raheed, Hobbs asked the group to list the district's five main needs. <br>
<br>
No. 1 turned out to be security, followed by medicine, stable currency and electric power. There was no No. 5. <br>
<br>
Hobbs told the gathering security is also a major U.S. priority, and promised to return to patrol the area that night. <br>
<br>
As for medical supplies, he said, Army medics would be in the area within a day. <br>
